SIMPLE: rob
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rob
<hw>Rob</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.; cf. Sp.
<ets>rob</ets>, It. <ets>rob</ets>, <ets>robbo</ets>, Pg.
<ets>robe</ets>, <ets>arrobe</ets>, Ar. <ets>rubb</ets>,
<ets>robb</ets>, Per. <ets>rub</ets>.]</ety> <def>The inspissated juice
of ripe fruit, obtained by evaporation of the juice over a fire till it
acquires the consistence of a sirup. It is sometimes mixed with honey or
sugar.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>rhob</asp>, and
<asp>rohob</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rob</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rob
<hw>Rob</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Robbed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Robbing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>rober</ets>, of German
origin; cf. OHG. <ets>roub<?/n</ets>, G. <ets>rauben</ets>, and OHG.
<ets>roub</ets> robbing, booty, G. <ets>raub</ets>. ⟦root⟧114. See
<er>Reave</er>,and cf. <er>Robe</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take
(something) away from by force; to strip by stealing; to plunder; to
pillage; to steal from.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who would <qex>rob</qex> a hermit of his weeds,⟦br⟧
His few books, or his beads, or maple dish?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that is <qex>robbed</qex>, not wanting what is stolen,⟦br⟧
Let him not know it, and he's not <qex>robbed</qex> at all.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To be executed for <qex>robbing</qex> a church.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To take the property of (any one)
from his person, or in his presence, feloniously, and against his will,
by violence or by putting him in fear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deprive of, or withhold from, unjustly or
injuriously; to defraud; <as>as, to <ex>rob</ex> one of his rest, or of
his good name; a tree <ex>robs</ex> the plants near it of
sunlight.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I never <qex>robbed</qex> the soldiers of their pay.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rob</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rob
<hw>Rob</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To take that which belongs to
another, without right or permission, esp. by violence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am accursed to <qex>rob</qex> in that thief's company.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Robalito</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Robalo</ent>⟦br⟧
